Abstract¶

This informal report is for the pitch session. The first 3 steps of data exploration have been completed. This report is composed of 3 parts: Introduction and background, exploratory data analysis, and three questions I would answer from this data.

Introduction and background¶

About the dataset¶

In this report, I concentrated on Wisconsin Diagnostic Breast Cancer (WDBC) dataset. Features in this dataset are computed from a digitized image of a fine needle aspirate (FNA) of a breast mass. They describe the characteristics of the cell nuclei present in the image with 32 attributes. The dataset is available on the UCI machine learning repository (https://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/datasets/Breast+Cancer+Wisconsin+%28Diagnostic%29).

Attributes:

1: Id number

2: Diagnosis: malignant; benign

3 - 32: ten real-valued features computed for each cell nucleus.

a: radius

b: texture (standard deviation of gray-scale values)

c: perimeter

d: area

e: smoothness

f: compactness

g: concavity

h: concave points

i: symmetry

j: fractal dimension

The mean, standard error, and "worst" or largest (mean of the three largest values) of these features were computed for each image, resulting in 30 features. For instance, field 3 is Mean Radius, field 13 is Radius SE, field 23 is the Worst Radius.

About the external data set¶

The external dataset I found is Wisconsin Prognostic Breast Cancer (WPBC) dataset, which also can be found at the UCI machine learning repository (https://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/datasets/Breast+Cancer+Wisconsin+%28Prognostic%29). This dataset has 198 number of instances and 35 attributies.

Attributes:

1: Id number

2: Outcome: R = recur, N = nonrecur

3: Time: recurrence time if field 2 = R, disease free time if field 2 = N

4 - 33: ten real-valued features are computed for each cell nucleus, which is the same with field 3 - 32 in WDBC dataset.

34: Tumor size: diameter of the excised tumor in centimeters

35: Lymph node statis: number of positive axillary lymph nodes.7. Now take a look at the external dataset

Study purpose¶

The goal of my project is to classify the diagnosis by different features of nuclei and to find out if there is a relationship between diagnosis and breast cancer recurrence.

From the boxplots above, we can find that some features look similar. For example, symmetry_worst and fractal dimension_worst feature in group 3. But how can we decide whether these features are correlated with each other or not? If some of the features are correlated with each other, then we can just keep one of them and drop the others. This is my first question raise from the boxplot.

The swarm plots can show variance clearly. To interpret the plot above, in radius_mean, texture_mean , perimeter_mean, area_mean, concavity_mean, concave points_mean features, the median of the Malignant and Benign looks like separated so it can be good for classification. Whereas in smoothness_mean, compactness_mean, symmetry_mean, and fractal_dimension_mean features, hmedian of the Malignant and Benign does not looks like separated so it does not give good information for classification.

The WPBC dataset do not have any missing values. My third question is to investigate the relationship between diagnosis outcome and recurrence.

3. Questions¶

1: Investigate which features have a correlation with each other so that we could just keep one of them for classification.

2: Find out which features have little attributes towards classification (I will use PCA for this part) and do the classification by the remained features.

3: Merge the WDBC and WPBC dataset and find out if there is a relationship between diagnosis outcome and recurrence.
